<DOC><DOCNO> AP890522-0201 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1924EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     05-22 0171</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0175</SECOND><HEAD>Increased Fighting Reported at Kandahar</HEAD><DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Moslem rebels killed 61 soldiers inweekend attacks around Kandahar in southeastern Afghanistan, theguerrillas' Afghan News Agency reported Monday.   It said Latif Aryan, identified as the provincial chief ofsecret police, and four of his agents were among those killed.   Other rebel sources earlier reported increased fighting aroundthe battered, ancient city where rebels have put communist forcesunder intermittent siege for almost two years.   ANA said mujahedeen, or Islamic ``holy warriors,'' concentratedweekend rocket attacks on Kandahar's military airport, destroying ajet bomber, a tank, two other vehicles and a fuel pumping station.The agency said four mujahedeen were wounded. There was noindependent confirmation.   Both sides in the Afghan war often make exaggerated andcontradicting claims and verification is rarely possible.   The Soviet-backed People's Democratic Party of Afghanistanseized power in a bloody 1978 coup. Mujahedeen, backed mainly byPakistan and the United States, are fighting to topple it andestablish an Islamic system of government.</TEXT></DOC>